The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Marginal decline in Lever profit 
                                                                                                               Marginal decline in Lever profit 
          OUR BUREAU                              
	Calcutta, July 28: Hindustan Unilevers first-quarter net profit fell 2.69 per cent to Rs 543.19 crore from Rs 558.18 crore during the corresponding period last fiscal.        
	Net sales, however, rose 7.77 per cent to Rs 4,475.68 crore during the quarter ended June 30 from Rs 4,152.84 crore during the same period last year.        
	The domestic FMCG business grew 12.80 per cent to Rs 4,148.66 crore from Rs 3,677.92 crore during the first quarter last year.         
	Exports fell 34.72 per cent to Rs 255.58 crore from Rs 391.51 crore.        
	Hindustan Unilevers home and personal care segment reported sales of Rs 3,405.82 crore during the first quarter, registering a growth of 11.87 per cent over Rs 3,044.53 crore during the same period a year ago.        
	Soaps and detergents grew 10 per cent, while personal products rose 15 per cent.         
	The foods business jumped 17.28 per cent to Rs 742.84 crore from Rs 633.39 crore.         
	Beverages grew 19 per cent with all brands showing good growth. Lipton Theanine Tea was launched in this quarter.         
	Processed foods delivered volume-led growth of 15 per cent, driven by Kissan and Annapurna. Ice-creams grew well at 23 per cent, again led by volumes.        
	Other income fell 14.35 per cent to Rs 71.44 crore from Rs 83.41 crore during a year ago.         
	We have taken decisive actions to strengthen our competitiveness and execution capabilities in the marketplace. These have started to show positive results with good volume recovery in personal products and foods, chairman Harish Manwani said.        
	Cost management        
	Manwani said significant cost effectiveness had helped improve operating margins and the company would continue to focus on profitable growth.         
	Lower input costs combined with tight cost management have led to higher operating margins in this quarter.                                                                                                                                                    
